  "prompt": "Does it matter where I do my masters?",
  "response": "The importance of where you do your master's degree depends on several factors:\n\n1. Field of Study\n- Some fields are more reputation-sensitive (e.g., business, law, engineering)\n- Technical and research-heavy fields may place more emphasis on specific program strengths\n\n2. Career Goals\n- Research-oriented careers often value program reputation more\n- Some industries care more about skills and experience than university name\n\n3. Reputation and Rankings\n- Top-tier universities can provide:\n- Better networking opportunities\n- Higher-quality education\n- Potentially stronger job prospects\n- More respected credentials\n\n4. Program-Specific Factors\n- Faculty expertise\n- Research opportunities\n- Industry connections\n- Curriculum quality\n\n5. Financial Considerations\n- Cost of program\n- Potential scholarship opportunities\n- Return on investment\n\n6. Personal Fit\n- Location\n- Program culture\n- Specific courses offered\n- Research opportunities\n\n7. Industry Specifics\n- Some fields are more credential-sensitive than others\n- Tech and academia often value program reputation more\n- Some industries focus more on skills and experience\n\nGenerally, while the institution matters, it's not the only factor. Your performance, skills, networking, and how you leverage the opportunity are equally important.",
